com.misc.common.moplaf.solver

Interface Generator

  • All Superinterfaces:
    org.eclipse.emf.ecore.EObject, org.eclipse.emf.common.notify.Notifier, com.misc.common.moplaf.job.Run, com.misc.common.moplaf.job.RunParams
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    GeneratorImpl

    public interface Generator
extends com.misc.common.moplaf.job.Run
    A representation of the model object 'Generator'.

    A Generator is a problem formulation (linear, constraints, ...), containing

    • a set of variables: GeneratorVar
    • a set of constraints: GeneratorCons
    • a set of goals: GeneratorGoal

    SolutionProviders (typically, Solvers) will produce Solutions for this problem formulation.

    A Generator is structured as follows:

    • a Generator is a set of trees (a forest) of tuples: GeneratorTuple
    • a Generator has GeneratorTuple roots
    • a GeneratorTuple has GeneratorTuple elements (children) and possibly a GeneratorTuple container (parent)
    • a GeneratorTuple, has : GeneratorTupleMember members
    • there are two kinds of GeneratorTupleMembers
      • variables: GeneratorVar
      • constraints: GeneratorCons

    A generator provides

    • a mechanism allowing to traverse all the tuples:
      • interface ITupleVisitor
      • method visitTuples(ITupleVisitor)
    • helpers to construct itself:
      • method generateRootTuples(): generate the roots of the structure
      • method generateTuples(): generate the tuples of the structure, starting from the roots
      • method generateTupleXReferences(): set XReferences after the structure has been built
    • helpers to construct the variables and the constraints:
      • method generateVars(): construct the variables
      • method generateCons(): construct the constraints
      • method generateGoals(): construct the goals

    Concrete Generator implementations will

    • subclass Generator and GeneratorTuple
    • implement the Generate methods in order to
      • create the GeneratorTuples, so the structure of the formulation
      • create the variables and constraints hanging to the elements of this structure
      • create the goals defined for this formulation

    A generator may select one solution among its pool of solutions: setSelected(Solution). The selected solution is used to show properties of this Generator elements for the selected solution.

    The following features are supported:

    • Tuple Root
    • Goals
    • Generator Feature Modes
    • Solution Provider
    • Remarks
    • Footprint Nof Vars
    • Footprint Nof Cons
    • Footprint Nof Terms
    • Code
    • Selected
